6":"1426","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1324":"1324","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","Abt. 1300":"about 1300","about 1297":"about 1297","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Basford, Nottinghamshire, England":"Basford, Nottinghamshire, England","Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","of Colwick, Nottinghamshire, England":"Colwick, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Colewick","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Colwick (Nottinghamshire), but in the West Midlands perhaps alternatively from Colewick (lost, in Saint Johns in Bedwardine, Worcestershire) or Colewich (Staffordshire), for which see also   Colledge  . The placenames are formed either with the Old English personal name <i>Cola</i> or with Old English <i>col</i> ‘coal, charcoal’ + Old English <i>wic</i> ‘dairy farm’ (see   Wick  ). The surname <i>Colwick</i> is no longer found in Britain. Compare   Collick  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Collick","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>collok</i> ‘tankard, bowl, or pail’.","habitational name from any of several places, including Colhook Common in Petworth (Sussex), Colwick in Nottinghamshire (see   Colwick  ), and perhaps a lost or unidentified place in Somerset or Devon."]},{"name":"Colledge","meanings":["English (Midlands and northern England): habitational name from Colwich in Staffordshire, named from Old English <i>col</i> ‘(char)coal’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘building’. The name has become associated with the familiar word <i>college</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":15,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":28,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":37,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William de Colewick II was born about 1300, in Nottinghamshire, England, his father, Sir John Colewick, was 21 and his mother, Joan Staunton, was 20. He married Joan Peche in 1341, in Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 23 October 1361, in his hometown, at the age of 62."},"et":{"Abt. 1300–23 October 1361":"umbes 1300–23. oktoober 1361","1300–1361":"1300–1361","1320–1361":"1320–1361","1324–1426":"1324–1426","1281–1362":"1281–1362","1281–1335":"1281–1335","1341":"1341","1362":"1362","1361":"1361","1281":"1281","23 October 1361":"23. oktoober 1361","1426":"1426","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1324":"1324","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","Abt. 1300":"umbes 1300","about 1297":"umbes 1297","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Basford, Nottinghamshire, England":"Basford, Nottinghamshire, England","Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Colwick, Nottinghamshire, England":"Colwick, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt. 1300–23 October 1361":"noin 1300–23. lokakuuta 1361","1300–1361":"1300–1361","1320–1361":"1320–1361","1324–1426":"1324–1426","1281–1362":"1281–1362","1281–1335":"1281–1335","1341":"1341","1362":"1362","1361":"1361","1281":"1281","23 October 1361":"23. lokakuuta 1361","1426":"1426","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1324":"1324","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","Abt. 1300":"noin 1300","about 1297":"noin 1297","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Basford, Nottinghamshire, England":"Basford, Nottingham